Overview:
The 3-15x50 Tactical Riflescope (Matte Black) from Weaver has been specially engineered for tactical applications. It has been manufactured to the strictest tolerances in order to perform in the harshest environments. The 3-15x50 Tactical riflescope is waterproof, fogproof and shockproof. It has a 30mm, single piece tube construction. This riflescope is endowed with a Mil-Dot reticle and has fully multicoated lenses that contribute to the brightness and contrast of the optics. Locating the reticle in the first focal plane allows the size of the pattern to increase as the magnification is increased. This is preferred by many tactical groups for use as a point of aim and as a means of measurement. 

The side focus feature allows parallax adjustment to keep the reticle and target aligned regardless of the shooters head position. An extra-hard coating on the exterior lens surfaces protects the optics from the scratches and abrasions that all too often occur in the rough and tumble world of tactical endeavors. The P-32 is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the .32 Auto cartridge. The firing mechanism is double action only. The magazine has a 7 round capacity. 
The KEL-TEC P-32 is the lightest .32 Auto pistol ever made. Thanks to its locking dynamics and superior ergonometry, perceived recoil and practical accuracy are comparable to much larger guns. 
The P-32 is mainly intended for plainclothes police officers as a secondary weapon or for concealed carry by licensed citizens. The small grip size and light trigger pull make the P-32 ideal for female shooters. 
From the very beginning of the design and development, computers have been used exclusively. All machined components are also made on modern high speed computerized equipment.

 The P-32 has six main component groups: barrel, slide, firing mechanism, grip, and magazine. The barrel is made of SAE 4140 ordnance steel, heat treated to 48 HRC. The slide is also 4140 steel, 
and contains the firing pin and the extractor. The rectangular frame is machined from solid 7075-T6 aluminum and houses the firing mechanism. The trigger connects via a transfer bar to the hammer. 
The hammer is driven by a novel free floating extension spring. The light weight firing pin transmits the energy of the hammer to ignite the primer. After firing, the hammer block holds the hammer away from 
the firing pin, providing a mechanical safety.

postcontent:
New Bolt Carrier Group! 

(I take credit cards)

I just installed a new DTI Mil Spec BCG ($110.00) at no additional cost.

This is my fight-like-you-train rifle.

It’s a true Mil-Spec M4A1 SOPMOD Block 1 Clone, I’ve just gone over it with a fine comb, refurbished, repainted, and recoated everything that needed fixin’. It’s better than new.
I’m willing to part with it in one of three configurations (top to bottom on third picture):

1.	“Bare Bones” $700.00
•	Brand new plastic AR-15 handguards

•	Brand new Knights Armament Rail Adaptive System 
•	Taupe (tan/FDEish) grips and rail covers 
•	Brand new* B5 Systems 6-Position enhanced SOPMOD stock ($95.00 value)
•	Brand New MaTech Mil-Spec BUIS
•	1 windowed* FDE P-Mag

SPECS:
The barrel is 14.5” and has a 1/7 Twist. It also has a .25”special spacer and A2 flash-hider attached to make it a legal 16” (so no need for BATFE-NFA forms or tax stamps.)

The spacer has a larger bore than the barrel, so the gas pressure in this weapon is as close as you can get to an actual M4, same goes for muzzle velocity (depending on ammo.) This means that it cycles and recoils (and rises) like the real deal. It also fixes the reliability issue 16” direct impingement AR carbines sometimes have.

"BARREL LENGTH STUDIES IN 5.56MM NATO WEAPONS"
(http://www.sadefensejournal.com/wp/?p=1093)

The trigger is Mil-Spec and single stage. It’s polished to perfection, it’s one of the smoothest, crispest Mil-Spec triggers you will ever encounter.

The front post is F marked, the upper has M4 feed ramps, and the buffer is Heavy (H marked.) The grips and rail covers are masterfully coated.

*New as of the day of this posting, I’m using the rifle in the SOPMOD conifg so some components may show signs of battle wear if you take too long making up your mind.

Chinese AK’s are acclaimed as some of the best, surpassing Russians and other slavic nations, this rifle is a true testament to that quality. Made in the same factory as the Chinese Military’s Type 56 this rifle features many milled parts, a fully chrome lined barrel, and a gorgeous blued finish which is very rare amongst the slew of painted matte black and parkerized ak’s on the market today.

title: For Sale:  Buy M1 Garands direct from non-profit CMP
postcontent:
The Civilian Marksmanship Program, founded by Theodore Roosevelt to promote marksmanship, is a non-profit org that has been charged with warehousing and distributing these gems. You can buy surplus M1 Garand rifles for $695 or even less directly from CMP, rather than paying $1000 to someone here on Armslist.

Go to thecmp.org for details, but it is simple to do:

Mail a copy of Birth Certificate, Proof of firearms training like CCW or class certificate, membership in a CMP affiliated group like Wisconsin FORCE or Glock GSSF and the CMP order forms. They FedEx the rifle to your door for $30.

Don't support price gouging on Armslist. Plus, you'd have to be out of your tree to trust a word any of these guys tell you about their great "collector" gun.
